When I was five years old and starting to read, my dear grandfather Carlos Felipe gave me an adventure book.
&quot;Microbe Hunters&quot; by Paul de Kruif.
In its chapters were Leeuwenhoek, Spallanzani, Koch, the one with the bacillus, Pasteur, men who with rudimentary microscopes sought to defeat the invisible enemy.
The book did not awaken in me a vocation for medicine or chemistry, but it did awaken my passion for history.
And, as a frequent traveler to the past, I wanted to tell you something about the pandemics that hit humanity.
We could talk about the ferocious cholera of the second half of the 19th century, or the smallpox that cost so much to control.
But there are two pandemics that were very marked by their fatal consequences.
In the fourteenth century, the black plague, caused by a louse that moved on rats.
It started in Asia and from there it went to Venice, the most cosmopolitan port of its time.
That&#39;s how he got into Europe.
Mortality was between 25 and 50 million.
One out of every four Europeans was carried away by the plague.
The numbers in Asia were quite similar.
Closer in time, in the 20th century, the century of flu, we had the Spanish flu in 1918.
Spanish flu that began in the US with American soldiers preparing to leave at the end of World War I and that infected the populations of the French ports where they embarked.
From there it spread throughout the continent.
It started in the US and came to Europe through France.
Why do we call it Spanish flu?
Well, that was &quot;fake news&quot;.
The government and the press of Spain decided to confront the evil by putting the statistics on the surface.
Due to this honesty of the data and the numbers, they ended up being pointed out as responsible for something that did not correspond to them.
At that time, one in five infected died.
Look, in World War I, between 10 and 30 million people died.
The universal flu killed 50 million.
The world population fell between 2.5% and 5% because of that pandemic.
We are talking about cholera, smallpox, the black plague, the universal flu and we could also add the yellow fever of 1871, which struck the cities of Corrientes and Buenos Aires.
What did they all have in common?
That when they attacked us we weren&#39;t warned.
We were not prepared.
To make matters worse, in many of the cases it was not known where the contagion came from.
Therefore, the responses and reactions were not effective in countering the evil.
What did we learn from all those fatalities?
Something very important, that the dangerousness of the virus is enhanced by misinformation.
I explain them.
In the fourteenth century, instead of dealing with rats and poor hygiene, it was argued that the sinful lifestyle of many had unleashed divine wrath.
In the 20th century, instead of showing the true causes of that flu, reality was distorted and the bug was out of control.
In this way it spread to the five continents.
Therefore, we may have learned at once that we must deal with the truth.
As much as it hurts us.
Another of the great lessons on that occasion was that we are going to have to stay on our guard even after the storm passes.
Because there have always been second and third waves that have caught the unawares.
But, above all, we can venture wonderful times of growth.
Because after the black plague the Renaissance arose.
Because after the universal flu came the 1920s, the most fruitful and avant-garde of all time.
Yes, at the end of the tunnel, the sun awaits us.
Thank you.
