&quot;We are letting terrorists in.&quot;
&quot;We are losing identity.&quot;
And it is true that there are also people who are very in favor of or empathize with people who are fleeing the war, but I can also verify that among these people there is a kind of hiding behind the mistakes of politicians in order not to act, to not participate in initiatives that can, if not resolve, at least alleviate these very serious personal dramas.
In the informal discourse and in the official discourse, learning German is highlighted as key to the integration of refugees.
I am from Barcelona, I am a linguist.
I have been living in Cologne, Germany for four years, and learning the language is also a key factor for me in order to be able to integrate, but it is not only a key factor for refugees, but for all immigrants in general.
I have been researching different aspects of language in multilingual environments for several years, and for me language is not a final product that can be mastered.
For me, language is a process that changes throughout life, through the personal experiences we have.
Obviously, language is a powerful instrument of integration, of inclusion, but also a powerful instrument of social exclusion.
If, for example, you have poor linguistic competence or you have a foreign accent, or a certain dialect of a region, or, perhaps, you have some type of disability that affects the production of oral language, such as , stuttering, these are all examples that influence how people will accept you or marginalize you in a society.
The use of language and identity is not something static, it is something that changes.
It is not like fingerprints, which is what accompanies you all your life.
Identity is something that is created or forged based on the values and beliefs that your family gives you, your friends give you, and it also depends on what you really want to be, and what you really want to be depends on depending on your motivation, the feeling of belonging that you have with other groups with which you feel related or identified and also depending on the interactions with groups that are totally different from you.
Free German classes are offered in refugee centers in Germany, and one might think, it is natural to think, that these people should be happy to be able to receive these German courses and also that they should be grateful.
But the absence of adolescent girls in these German groups, in these activities, is really significant.
Put yourself in a situation: these girls carry a lot of burden, many post-traumatic disorders, due to an exodus, to a land that no one had promised them, they have seen their loved ones murdered, they have seen their houses burned or bombed, unfortunately others have also been witnesses or victims of violations in their particular movement from Afghanistan, Iraq and Syria on their way to Europe, or on the way in this case to Germany.
If you put yourself in their shoes, would you want to take German classes or anything else?
To make matters worse, the families of these girls, parents, brothers or other relatives, prevent them from participating in these activities because they think that, perhaps, they will harm them even more.
And the question is: what to do so that these girls begin to participate in this new society and that they can integrate?
This is the question four of our friends asked ourselves: with the red sweater, Sandra, then there&#39;s me, Lina and Peter.
The four of us, for different reasons, have a lot to do with adolescence.
Peter and I, for having fifteen-year-old daughters.
And Sandra and Lina, for also working with this group, adolescence.
We thought: what if we do a project where it is not only attractive for refugee girls, but also attractive for German girls?
Could we get them together?
Could we create a space for them to interact and perhaps with that we could contribute to transforming their identity?
This is how the HalloFoto! initiative was born.
It is an intercultural project for adolescent girls between 13 and 17 years old.
The objectives of this project were: to develop... well, first to create these spaces for interaction in order to develop communication skills.
And the creative powers of the girls.
We thought: if we develop both things, surely we will create the possibility that they also develop intercultural competences.
Obviously, to develop communication skills you had to go through learning German, there was no other option, and we used an innovative method: augmentative communication boards.
Augmentative communication boards are aids for people who are non-verbal, that is, people who do not have oral language.
This condition can occur from birth, for example in the case of children with severe autism spectrum disorders, or for example in children with cerebral palsy.
This condition can also occur when you are an adult, because you have a stroke or because you have an accident, or because you suffer from a neurodegenerative disease, such as Parkinson&#39;s.
These boards that we used for the project are made up of pictograms and the core vocabulary.
The core vocabulary is the words that are repeated the most in the spontaneous language and this happens not only in German, but also in Spanish, Catalan, Basque, English, etc.
The truth is that the girls accepted these instruments very well, and the data collected in the project show that, yes, they value it positively.
In any case, for them this is not the determining factor to learn German, to have dreams, to be motivated, to really want to participate in this new society.
For them, what is really significant are the meetings that we form, that we organize in HalloFoto!, in our project.
They are intercultural encounters because we were encouraging face-to-face interaction between groups with totally different frames of reference.
This, for example, is the image of one of the meetings.
We organize these intercultural meetings by theme and the themes were decided by them.
This is the theme &quot;Makeup and hairdressing&quot;.
In another of the meetings we went to an adventure center where there were zip lines, there were balancing games, tunnels.
The issue was not creating fear, but overcoming fear.
Together they helped each other, and it was not a question of who was more or less afraid, which group was the most or least afraid, it was simply each one in their expression.
You can see it in their faces, they can&#39;t define who is who, the one who is afraid.
The point is that in this, along with other meetings... —This is the meeting we did about cooking. —they see meaning.
And it is in this construction of meaning what generates a sensation of miscegenation, a sensation of creating links, intercultural developments that go beyond labels.
The only thing that labels do is generate stereotypes and generate prejudices that do not account for the great wealth that each of us is, or that each of us has.
In addition to communication skills, we also wanted to develop creative skills.
Creativity is the affective and cognitive expression of each individual.
And if we activate that expression jointly, first, a space develops to generate things, initially unthinkable, which are mixtures of expressions where one can already begin to see how an intercultural competence is being forged.
